<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="542" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="31.[813,1456,217,722]" box="[813,957,217,243]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[813,1456,217,722]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">
Shell minute, depressed, with a flat spire and wide umbilicus. Protoconch of a little less than 1 whorl. Teleoconch with three strong spiral ridges, of which one is adapical, the strongest one is on the periphery, and one is abapical. Microsculpture of irregularly arranged granules, loosely aligned axially, which give the surface a shagreened aspect and are attenuated on the ridges; the last 1/4 whorl marked in addition by conspicuous growth lines. Umbilicus broad and wide, delimited by an additional internal ridge. Aperture simple, rounded on the parietal and columellar side, polygonal along the outer lip, reflecting the termination of the ridges. Columellar edge of the aperture reflected outwards and strongly receding where approaching the parietal edge, abutting there on the abapical ridge of the preceding whorl. Dimensions of the 
<typeStatus box="[1353,1451,664,690]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">holotype</typeStatus>
: 
<quantity box="[813,913,695,722]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" unit="mm" value="0.35">0.35 mm</quantity>
height × 
<quantity box="[1016,1102,696,722]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
diameter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="542" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[813,1456,759,1519]" box="[813,913,759,785]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[813,1456,759,1519]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">
The size, profile, and the characteristic recession of the abapical part of the aperture support the placement of this species in 
<taxonomicName authority="Iredale, 1917" authorityName="Iredale" authorityYear="1917" box="[813,931,855,881]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,931,855,881]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">Orbitestella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The protoconch is damaged on the only available specimen and could not be observed properly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[813,1456,759,1519]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">
This minute species does not resemble closely any other gastropod known to us from the eastern Atlantic. The most similar is 
<taxonomicName authority="Mestayer, 1919" authorityName="Mestayer" authorityYear="1919" box="[913,1301,982,1009]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hinemoa">
<emphasis box="[913,1128,982,1008]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">Orbitestella hinemoa</emphasis>
Mestayer, 1919
</taxonomicName>
, from off New Zealand, which differs only in having a more even development of the three keels on the last whorl, the peripheral one not so much protruding as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Ortega &amp; Gofas, 2019" authorityName="Ortega &amp; Gofas" authorityYear="2019" box="[1130,1345,1078,1104]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pruinosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1130,1345,1078,1104]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">Orbitestella pruinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1351,1409,1079,1105]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The only other species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Iredale, 1917" authorityName="Iredale" authorityYear="1917" box="[1042,1161,1110,1136]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1042,1161,1110,1136]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">Orbitestella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described from the eastern Atlantic and Mediterranean area is 
<taxonomicName authority="(Liuzzi &amp; Zucchi Stolfa, 1979)" authorityName="Iredale" authorityYear="1917" baseAuthorityName="Liuzzi &amp; Zucchi Stolfa" baseAuthorityYear="1979" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="dariae">
<emphasis box="[1174,1270,1142,1168]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">O. dariae</emphasis>
(Liuzzi &amp; Zucchi Stolfa, 1979)
</taxonomicName>
, recorded from Madeira by 
<bibRefCitation author="SEGERS W. &amp; SWINNEN F. &amp; DE PRINS R." box="[1248,1450,1174,1200]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" refId="ref24938" refString="SEGERS W., SWINNEN F. &amp; DE PRINS R. 2009. - Marine Molluscs of Madeira. Snoeck Publishers, Heule, Belgium, 612 p." type="book" year="2009">
Segers 
<emphasis box="[1319,1369,1174,1200]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">et al.</emphasis>
(2009)
</bibRefCitation>
. It has a similar outline but an evenly convex abapical part with several flat spiral cords, and a spiral series of prominent knobs on the adapical side; furthermore it lacks the shagreened microsculpture of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ortega &amp; Gofas, 2019" authorityName="Ortega &amp; Gofas" authorityYear="2019" box="[1016,1142,1302,1328]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pruinosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1016,1142,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">O. pruinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1151,1213,1302,1328]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The specimen from a deep-water thanatocenosis off Sardinia, Western Mediterranean, figured as 
<taxonomicName authority="Iredale, 1917" authorityName="Iredale" authorityYear="1917" baseAuthorityName="Liuzzi &amp; Zucchi Stolfa" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[1012,1112,1365,1392]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="dariae">
<emphasis box="[1012,1112,1365,1392]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">O. dariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="BONFITTO A. &amp; OLIVERIO M. &amp; SABELLI B. &amp; TAVIANI M." box="[1154,1386,1365,1392]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" pagination="141 - 157" refId="ref21850" refString="BONFITTO A., OLIVERIO M., SABELLI B. &amp; TAVIANI M. 1994. - A Quaternary deep marine molluscan assemblage from East Sardinia (Western Tyrrhenian Sea). Bollettino Malacologico 30 (5 - 9): 141 - 157." type="journal article" year="1994">
Bonfitto 
<emphasis box="[1253,1305,1365,1391]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">et al.</emphasis>
(1994)
</bibRefCitation>
is not that species and is so similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ortega &amp; Gofas, 2019" authorityName="Ortega &amp; Gofas" authorityYear="2019" box="[1162,1286,1397,1423]" class="Gastropoda" family="Orbitestellidae" genus="Orbitestella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pruinosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1162,1286,1397,1423]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="542">O. pruinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1295,1355,1398,1424]" pageId="31" pageNumber="542" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
that it is possibly the same; their specimen differs from the Canarian one in having definite axial riblets between the spiral ridges, instead of loosely aligned granules.
</paragraph>
